    <title>Combined summary - Re-enabling simple tx replacement</title>
    <updated>2023-06-09T15:16:52.130146+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-January/007077.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Ross Nicoll has developed a functional prototype for atomic cross-chain trading between the Bitcoin and Dogecoin blockchains. However, he encountered issues with transaction locking while attempting to develop atomic cross-chain trading between the two blockchains. He reported a bug in Bitcoin's protocol related to transaction locking, sharing a test case where the transaction wouldn't lock until January 5th. Nicoll tried moving the wallet.dat file and attempting the spend transaction, but it was either rejected upon acceptance to mempool or never included in a block. Nicoll drafted a patch to address this issue, proposing TX replacement when all conflicting transactions are not final and the replacement is final. However, concerns were raised about potential denial of service attacks with this patch. Gregory Maxwell expressed concerns about potential bandwidth expansion compared to a non-replacement, but Nicoll argued that only one replacement could take place, and any further replacements would be attempting to replace a final transaction, which would fail.In an email exchange on January 4, 2015, between Gregory Maxwell and Ross Nicoll, Maxwell requested the actual raw transaction and confirmed that it would be a severe bug if unlocked transactions were being relayed or mempooled far in advance. Nicoll mentioned that non-final transactions could only be replaced with final transactions, to which Maxwell responded that he missed that the replacement had to be final. Nicoll planned to set up a few nodes to double-check if the latest version was relaying this issue.There was also a conversation between Gregory Maxwell and Peter Todd on January 4th, 2015, where Maxwell suggested that IsStandardTx should be enforced elsewhere to prevent non-mempooling from being bypassed in testnet. This issue did not occur on the actual network.Ross Nicoll has yet to raise a PR due to concerns about the amount of discussion that may occur on GitHub, preferring to discuss the issue on a mailing list. The use of code to present solutions allows for clear and concise communication between parties. It also helps to ensure accuracy and can aid in troubleshooting if any issues arise. Overall, the use of code in communication is a valuable tool that should be utilized more frequently.</summary>
